difference between powershell and git bash while using vscodeThe main difference is that PowerShell is an object-oriented Windows-native shell designed for deep Windows system administration, while Git Bash is a text-based emulation layer designed to run Linux/Unix commands on Windows.When used inside Visual Studio Code, both tools let you build apps, run scripts, and manage your version control, but they behave differently under the hood.Core ComparisonFeaturePowerShellGit BashOS ArchitectureWindows native (built into the OS).Linux/Unix emulation layer (MinGW64).Data HandlingPasses structured .NET objects.Passes raw string text.File SystemsUses \ by default (C:\Project).Uses / by default (/c/Project).Script Format.ps1 files..sh files.Performance in VS CodeLoads instantly.Slightly slower initial startup time.Key Differences in VS Code1. Command Syntax and ScriptingPowerShell: Uses consistent "Verb-Noun" commands called Cmdlets (e.g., Get-ChildItem). It is highly optimal if you write scripts interacting directly with the Windows Registry, Azure, or hypervisors.Git Bash: Allows you to run standard Linux utilities like ls, grep, awk, sed, and ssh-agent directly inside Windows. This makes it easier to copy and paste deployment commands or build scripts written for Mac or Linux environments.2. Ecosystem and ExtensionsPowerShell: Features deep integration via the official PowerShell Extension for VS Code. This provides robust linting, IntelliSense, and integrated visual debugging for your automation scripts.Git Bash: Relies entirely on text stream integration. Interactive utilities or CLI tools that require native Windows consoles sometimes require you to prefix commands with winpty (e.g., winpty docker exec ...) to avoid breaking the text output layout.3. Execution Policy RestrictionsPowerShell: Enforces an explicit execution security policy by default. When attempting to run custom scripts or activate Node/Python virtual environments (.venv), you may encounter a red script execution error unless you alter the policy using Set-ExecutionPolicy.Git Bash: Completely bypasses Windows execution policies, executing environment scripts instantly without throwing native permission hurdles.How to Switch Your Shell in VS CodeYou can swap between them at any time without resetting your project:Press Ctrl + Shift + P to display the command palette.Search for and click Terminal: Select Default Profile.Choose PowerShell or Git Bash from the drop-down menu.Open a new terminal (Ctrl + ~) to launch your new preferred environment.To help you choose the best fit, are you focusing on Windows system management or cross-platform web development (Node.js, Docker, Python)? Let me know what programming language or framework you plan to run.26 sitesOn Windows what is the difference between Git Bash vs ...Git Bash is the same bash shell you are used to on Linux and MacOS but instead compiled for Windows. It has the Git prefix with th...Stack OverflowVS Terminal / PowerShell Terminal / Git / Git Bash - The freeCodeCamp ForumHere's some information about using the terminal in VS Code, PowerShell, and Git Bash: * **VS Code terminal** * Easier to use beca...The freeCodeCamp ForumDifference between Git GUI, Git Bash, Git CMD - Stack OverflowUseful if you are already familiar with Windows cmd and you only work on Windows. Git Bash emulates a bash environment on windows.Stack OverflowShow allYou said: like ls-a was running in gitbash but not in terminaThe reason ls -a failed in PowerShell (your default VS Code terminal) is a syntax error.PowerShell requires a space between a command and its flags.Why It FailedPowerShell: Treats ls-a as a single, unknown command name. You must type ls -a (with a space).Git Bash: Uses a Linux shortcut mechanism (an alias). It maps ls-a directly to ls -A under the hood, so it works even without the space.The Best Fixes for PowerShellIf you want to stay in PowerShell, use these options:Add a space: Type ls -a or dir -Force.Use native PowerShell: Type Get-ChildItem -Force (this is what ls actually points to in Windows).How to Permanently Fix This in VS CodeIf you prefer the flexible, space-free typing style of Git Bash, you should make Git Bash your permanent terminal inside VS Code.Press Ctrl + Shift + P to open the Command Palette.Type and select Terminal: Select Default Profile.Choose Git Bash from the list.Kill your current terminal by clicking the Trash Can icon in the bottom panel.Open a new terminal (Ctrl + ~), and ls-a will now work perfectly every time.Are you currently setting up a Node.js, Python, or Git project? I can give you the specific shortcut commands you will need for that environment.12 sitesHow to setup enviroment (Visual Studio Code, Power Shell)24 Oct 2020 — I try to run the code in PowerShell ( Power Shell ) (that is the default terminal in VS Code), but it doesn't work.elixirforum.comWhy does an error keep popping up when "ls -a " is used?1 Mar 2021 — Why does an error keep popping up when "ls -a " is used? 1 This doesn't appear to have anything to do with JavaScript or discordj.Stack OverflowCHARMM-GUIThe shell is expecting a command consisting of a program and its options, separated by a space. But since we didn't use a space, i...CHARMM-GUIShow allYou said: so git works on linux commandsYes, Git Bash runs Linux commands because it includes a mini-Linux simulation environment called Bash (Bourne Again Shell).However, it is important to separate Git from Git Bash:1. Git (The Tool)Git is just a version control tool.It uses the exact same commands everywhere (git status, git commit, git push).It works perfectly inside PowerShell, Git Bash, Mac, or Linux.2. Git Bash (The Terminal)This is a Windows-only program wrapper.It bundles the Git tool together with a Linux terminal emulator.It translates Linux commands (like ls, cd, pwd, grep, and clear) into a format that Windows can understand.Why Developers Use It on WindowsMost web servers, cloud platforms, and development tools run on Linux. Using Git Bash inside VS Code lets you practice and use standard Linux commands without needing to switch your entire computer over to a Linux operating system.Are you learning Git to manage your source code history, or are you focusing on mastering Linux command-line basics right now?21 sitesGit Bash: Running Linux-Like Commands on Windows with Git Bash1 Oct 2023 — Git Bash: Running Linux-Like Commands on Windows with Git Bash Introduction: In a world where seamless collaboration between devel...MediumHow to Use Git Bash on Windows25 Apr 2022 — How to Use Git Bash on Windows Git Bash is a terminal emulator shell and limited Linux-like environment for Windows that lets you ...Petri IT KnowledgebaseHow to install Git on Windows with Git Bash12 Jul 2023 — Linux and macOS include command-line utilities from Unix which work with Git. Microsoft, on the other hand, uses its own Windows c...IONOSShow allYou said: by typing ls -h in terminal powershell it is howing hiddeen file but not readme that is the original fileTyping ls -h in PowerShell hid your README file because -h does not mean "hidden files" in PowerShell; it is short for the -Hidden filter.When you run ls -h, you are instructing PowerShell to exclusively look for hidden files and hide everything else. Because your README file is a normal, visible file, PowerShell hides it from the output.The SolutionTo view both normal files (like your README) and hidden files at the same time in PowerShell, use the -Force parameter.Type this command:powershellls -Force
Use code with caution.Why it happens (PowerShell vs. Linux)In Git Bash (Linux syntax): The command ls -a means "List all items" (both normal and hidden).In PowerShell (Windows syntax): ls is actually just a shortcut for a command named Get-ChildItem.Providing the -h flag activates the -Hidden parameter, filtering the terminal to show only files with the hidden attribute enabled.Providing the -Force flag tells PowerShell to drop all filters and show absolutely everything in the directory